+
+### 2. Layout Algorithms
+
+#### Force-Directed Layout (Primary)
+- **Algorithm**: Modified Fruchterman-Reingold
+- **Benefits**: Natural clustering, handles cycles well
+- **Implementation**: Iterative physics simulation
+- **Features**: 
+  - Repulsion between nodes prevents overlap
+  - Attraction along edges creates logical grouping
+  - Configurable parameters for different graph types
+
+#### Hierarchical Layout (Alternative)
+- **Algorithm**: Sugiyama-style layered layout
+- **Benefits**: Clear hierarchy visualization
+- **Use Case**: When call direction is important
+- **Features**:
+  - Layer assignment based on call depth
+  - Minimized edge crossings
+  - Proper ancestor-descendant relationships
+
+#### Grid-Based Layout (Simple)
+- **Algorithm**: Regular grid positioning
+- **Benefits**: Predictable, fast
+- **Use Case**: Small graphs or debugging
+- **Features**:
+  - Fixed grid spacing
+  - Alphabetical or usage-based ordering
+
